        "title": "Techfast: The State of DevOps",
        "excerpt":"DevOps has been around since ‚âà2008, in that period of time the World has been gifted with distributed version control, declarative pipelines, containers, serverless infrastructure, social coding platforms, Deep Neural Network frameworks and Large Language Models with GPTs on top.   It‚Äôs a crazy world of software, being eaten by software.   ‚Äî ‚ÄúWhere does that leave contemporary DevOps?‚Äùü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è   Good question!   The DORA 2024 report certainly helps in trying to answer it. It‚Äôs a 120 page report, based on a survey among more than 39K professionals. But we will break it down for you and serve it up in bite sized interesting lumps and then open up for discussions.   Our DORA, not theirs   Ours: DevOps Research and Assessment Institute (DORA)  Theirs: Digital Operational Resilience Act (DORA)   Although the EU Digital Operational Resilience Act is getting a lot of attention these days. It‚Äôs not the DORA  we‚Äôre referring to. In the DevOps world we have known DORA for exactly 10 years now ‚Äî as something else.   Since 2014 The DevOps Research and Assessment institute (DORA) has released their annual report on ‚ÄúState of DevOps‚Äù. Start the day with us over a coffee and a croissant :coffee::croissant:. We will share and discuss the highlights of this year‚Äôs anniversary report, recap on the four DORA metrics and facilitate a discussion üí¨ among DevOps peers.   Who Should Attend?   If you are a leader or a manger of initiatives or teams even remotely related to DevOps or DevX, then this is for you. If you are a hands-on professional DevOps‚Äôer then this is for you too. And who knows? ‚Äî Maybe together we sow the seed to a small community; a breakfast club where we can inspire each other with DevOpsy things the really interests us.   We will serve croissants, coffee, tea and fresh juice during the event.   We‚Äôre hosting the event in the center of Copenhagen   üëà click to expand for location details  The Tech Collective, Borgergade 111, K√∏benhavn&lt;  Metro station \"Marmorkirken\" and Train station \"√òsterport\" are only a few minutes walking distance. There is usually decent access to street parking in the area around Nyboder. And there are several Parking options in Borgergade. The address is Borgergade 111. We will be in the conference room called Fibiger.   It‚Äôs free to attend but registration is required   The event is kept cozy and mingle-friendly. The seats are limited to 25. We have a waiting list that opens when they are all taken. Sign up to that if you cant get a ticket. We will get you in if at all possible.   Any questions? Please don‚Äôt hesitate to reach out to me lars@lakruzz.com.  ","categories": [],
